# RFC-0015

# Model Class Registry (MCR)

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* RFC-0000 Core Object Model
* RFC-0008 Distributed Attestation Network
* RFC-0010 Distributed Verification Protocol
* RFC-0013 Capability Validation Specification
* RFC-0014 Validator Competency Framework

---

# 1. Purpose

The Model Class Registry (MCR) defines how AI model classes are declared, published, standardized and verified within the AiDN ecosystem.

AiDN verifies Model Classes rather than specific model implementations.

A Model Class represents a set of expected observable characteristics.

It does not prescribe a specific provider, implementation or execution strategy.

---

# 2. Design Principles

### MCR-1

Model Classes describe externally observable behavior.

They do not identify implementation details.

---

### MCR-2

Execution implementation remains private.

A Hypervisor is never required to disclose the underlying provider, execution topology or model source.

---

### MCR-3

Model Classes are public.

Validation Specifications are public.

Execution strategies remain private.

---

### MCR-4

Any participant MAY propose a new Model Class.

Support by the network determines whether the class becomes verifiable.

---

# 3. Model Class

Every Model Class SHALL contain:

```yaml
class_id:

display_name:

capability:

validation_specification:

competency_profile:

description:

status:
```

Example:

```yaml
class_id: opus-class

display_name: Opus4.x-class

capability:

- llm.chat

validation_specification:

cvs-llm-opus-v1

competency_profile:

vcf-opus-v1
```

---

# 4. Endpoint Declaration

Every public Endpoint SHALL declare exactly one Model Class.

Example:

```yaml
identity:

display_name:

Opus4.6-class

model_class:

opus-class
```

The display name is controlled by the operator.

The Model Class references the public validation definition.

---

# 5. Private Model Classes

Operators MAY create arbitrary private Model Classes.

Example:

```yaml
display_name:

Alex Internal Coding

model_class:

alex-coding-v2
```

Private classes are valid Endpoint metadata.

However,

Private Model Classes SHALL NOT participate in distributed validation until a Validation Specification exists.

---

# 6. Validation Eligibility

An Endpoint participates in distributed validation only if:

* its declared Model Class exists;
* the Model Class references an approved Validation Specification;
* Validators supporting that Capability exist.

Otherwise:

```text
Verification Status

Unsupported
```

The Endpoint remains usable.

The Endpoint simply cannot accumulate validation-based reputation.

---

# 7. Model Class Proposal

Any participant MAY publish a new Model Class Proposal.

A proposal SHALL include:

* proposed Model Class identifier;
* Capability;
* Validation Specification;
* Competency Profile;
* human-readable description;
* reference evaluation methodology.

The proposal becomes publicly visible immediately.

---

# 8. Community Adoption

Support for a proposed Model Class is voluntary.

Hypervisors MAY independently choose to support a proposal.

Network support gradually increases as additional Hypervisors:

* recognize the Model Class;
* implement the Validation Specification;
* certify Validators.

No central authority approves Model Classes.

---

# 9. Model Class Lifecycle

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2

[*] --> Private

Private --> Proposed

Proposed --> Supported

Supported --> Verifiable

Verifiable --> Standard

Standard --> Deprecated

Deprecated --> Archived

Archived --> [*]
```

### Private

Known only to the operator.

No network validation.

### Proposed

Published to the network.

Validation Specification is available.

Community review begins.

### Supported

Recognized by one or more Hypervisors.

Validators MAY begin implementation.

### Verifiable

Validation Specification is implemented.

Certified Validators exist.

Endpoints MAY participate in DAN.

### Standard

The Model Class has broad network support.

Validation is considered stable.

### Deprecated

The Model Class remains usable.

New deployments are discouraged.

### Archived

Historical support only.

No further validation development.

---

# 10. Observed Behavior

Validation does not determine implementation.

Validation determines observable behavior.

Observed behavior includes:

* instruction following;
* reasoning quality;
* latency characteristics;
* protocol compliance;
* Validation Confidence;
* Competency compatibility.

Execution implementation remains intentionally unknown.

---

# 11. Execution Privacy

The following information SHALL remain private:

* provider implementation;
* local versus remote execution;
* provider chain;
* orchestration logic;
* internal routing;
* execution topology.

Validators SHALL evaluate only observable behavior.

---

# 12. Bundle Identity

Bundle Identity consists of two independent elements.

Operator Declaration:

```yaml
display_name:

Opus4.6-class
```

Protocol Declaration:

```yaml
model_class:

opus-class
```

The display name may change.

The Model Class determines validation compatibility.

---

# 13. Endpoint Profile

Operators MAY publish additional descriptive metadata.

Examples include:

* strengths;
* limitations;
* recommended tasks;
* supported languages;
* usage examples.

Endpoint Profiles improve discovery and routing.

Profiles SHALL NOT influence validation results.

---

# 14. Architectural Principle

The network verifies capabilities, not brands.

The network verifies observable behavior, not implementation.

Model Classes standardize expected behavior while preserving complete execution privacy.
